---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="You Are Not Alone"
  description="The research on parental alienation — how many families are affected, what the evidence shows, and what it means for you. You are not alone in this."
>

  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="section section-dark" style="text-align:center; padding-block:6rem;">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow">The data</p>
      <h1>You Are Not Alone</h1>
      <p style="font-size:1.15rem; opacity:0.8; max-width:580px; margin-inline:auto; line-height:1.75;">
        One of the most painful aspects of parental alienation is the feeling that no one
        understands — that what is happening to you is too strange, too specific, too
        invisible for the world to recognise. The data tells a different story.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Stats -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="stats-grid">
        <div class="stat-card card">
          <div class="stat-big">22 million</div>
          <div class="stat-desc">children worldwide are estimated to be affected by parental alienation</div>
          <div class="stat-source">Gardner, R.A. (2002) — widely cited estimate; see also PASG research</div>
        </div>
        <div class="stat-card card">
          <div class="stat-big">11–15%</div>
          <div class="stat-desc">of children in high-conflict divorces show significant signs of parental alienation</div>
          <div class="stat-source">Bernet, W. et al. (2020), Journal of Child Custody</div>
        </div>
        <div class="stat-card card">
          <div class="stat-big">1 in 5</div>
          <div class="stat-desc">divorcing families experience significant alienating behaviours by one parent</div>
          <div class="stat-source">Various — including Harman, Kruk & Hines (2018)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="stat-card card">
          <div class="stat-big">Both</div>
          <div class="stat-desc">mothers and fathers are alienating parents — though the experiencing parent is statistically more often the father</div>
          <div class="stat-source">Harman, J.E. et al., multiple studies 2016–2022</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What the research shows -->
  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="container-narrow prose">
      <p class="section-label">What the evidence shows</p>
      <h2>What we know — and what it means</h2>

      <h3>Parental alienation is recognised as harmful</h3>
      <p>
        The psychological and medical communities have moved — slowly, but measurably — toward
        recognising parental alienation as a real phenomenon with serious effects on children.
        The American Psychological Association, the American Bar Association, and family court
        systems in multiple jurisdictions now acknowledge it, even if their responses vary widely.
      </p>

      <h3>Children suffer long-term harm</h3>
      <p>
        Research by Amy Baker and others documents the long-term effects on children who were
        alienated from a parent: higher rates of depression, anxiety, low self-esteem, difficulty
        forming trusting relationships, and — in many cases — eventual regret and grief when they
        understand what happened. This is why fighting for your relationship with your child is
        not futile: it matters for their future, not only yours.
      </p>

      <h3>You are statistically far from alone</h3>
      <p>
        If parental alienation affects even 11% of high-conflict divorces — a conservative
        estimate — and there are hundreds of thousands of such divorces per year in English-speaking
        countries alone, the number of affected parents runs into the millions. The isolation
        you feel is a result of stigma, legal confidentiality, and the shame that is imposed on
        alienated parents — not of rarity.
      </p>

      <h3>The legal system is behind</h3>
      <p>
        Family courts in most jurisdictions are not well-equipped to identify or respond to
        parental alienation. Judges, CAFCASS officers, and court-appointed therapists vary
        enormously in their understanding. This is why having a clear, evidence-based account
        of what is happening — and why — is so important if you are engaged in legal proceedings.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <section class="section section-dark" style="text-align:center;">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <h2>Find community with people who understand</h2>
      <p style="opacity:0.8; margin-bottom:2rem;">
        The statistics don't make the experience less painful. But they do mean there are
        people out there who know exactly what you're going through.
      </p>
      <div style="display:flex; gap:1rem; justify-content:center; flex-wrap:wrap;">
        <a href="/community" class="btn btn-primary">Join the Community</a>
        <a href="/free-guide" class="btn btn-outline-light">Get the Free Guide</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</BaseLayout>

<style>
.eyebrow {
  font-size: 0.78rem;
  font-weight: 600;
  letter-spacing: 0.1em;
  text-transform: uppercase;
  color: var(--color-amber-light);
  margin-bottom: 1rem;
}
.section-label {
  font-size: 0.78rem;
  font-weight: 600;
  letter-spacing: 0.1em;
  text-transform: uppercase;
  color: var(--color-amber);
  margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
}
.stats-grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr);
  gap: 1.5rem;
}
.stat-card { text-align: center; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
.stat-big {
  font-family: var(--font-serif);
  font-size: clamp(2rem, 4vw, 3rem);
  font-weight: 700;
  color: var(--color-green-deep);
  line-height: 1.1;
  margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
}
.stat-desc {
  font-size: 0.92rem;
  color: var(--color-charcoal);
  line-height: 1.6;
  margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
}
.stat-source {
  font-size: 0.75rem;
  color: var(--color-warm-grey);
  font-style: italic;
  line-height: 1.5;
}

@media (max-width: 900px) {
  .stats-grid { grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr); }
}
@media (max-width: 600px) {
  .stats-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
}
</style>
